# The Hard Way

You know how to use a standard `for` loop, right?

```dart
List<String> weapons = ['Sword', 'Axe', 'Bow'];
for (int i = 0; i < weapons.length; i++) {
  print( weapons[i] );
}
```
It works... but it feels clunky. Dart has a MUCH better way when dealing with collections!

## The Easy Way

The `for-in` loop automatically walks through every single item in your List or Set from start to finish.

```dart
List<String> weapons = ['Sword', 'Axe', 'Bow'];
for (String w in weapons) {
  print(w);
}
```
It creates a temporary variable (`w`) that holds the current item, and prints it. No indexes needed!

